	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Some questions about taunt and indirect aggro.</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#131619" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Am now a 65 warrior (but spent most of my EQ life as a mage, only recently switching), but still have some questions about how some aggro/hate lists work.  Any help would be apprciated.<br />
<br />
1.) How does indirect aggro affect hate lists?  Some examples are low health aggro, does a successful taunt when a mob a mob is focused on someone with low health vault you up on the hate list even if the mob is still not focused on you, or dies this situation side-step standard hate lists?  Similarily does a sitting toon generate some kind of &quot;temporary hate&quot; as evidenced by a caster sitting after nuking (or sending in a pet) getting the mobs attention, but standing up before it arrives, to have it refocus on the tank?<br />
<br />
2.) Pet's taunting.  I can tell that most mage pets out taunt me, as they are the critters being summoned when I try to move a mob around instead of me (and yes I ask the casters to turn the taunt off after, most times) and assuming that taunt puts a tank at the head of the hate, would a warrior and pet not &quot;share&quot; the top of a hate list, and pass each other back and forth if both were constantly taunting every 8 seconds? (related to #3)<br />
<br />
3.) I have noticed that having a pet in the group that is taunting seems to prevent the slower from being attacked, unless the slow comes before the pet attacks.  Do pets generate such subatantial aggro tthat they are that far ahead of warriors?  Is it that pet taunt is infalable?  (This might be a question better left on mage/necro boards, but it related directly to my function in group)<br />
<br />
4.) Is it efficient to share &quot;burst&quot; aggro with a paladin or SK, to have them pile on the aggro, then just take it back with a successful taunt, to keep the mob focused on the warrior for the remainder of the fight, in effect using the pal/sk aggro &quot;advantages&quot; and pairing them with the warrior hp/mitigation?<br />
<br />
I know some of those sound like very basic questions, but is just an attempt to understand some of the specific mechanics better.<br />
<br />
Rahwain</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
